Okay, here's what I've done:
- Rebased on a recent `master`;
- Moved `montage2d` from `skimage.util.montage.montage2d` to `skimage.util.montage2d` (renamed `montage.py` to `_montage.py` in the process);
- Exposed `montage2d` in the corresponding `skimage/util/__init__.py`;
- Deprecated `montage2d` in favour of `montage` (new function, see below) only for 1 release (i.e. for removal in 0.15);

- Removed the implementation of `montage_rgb` and wrote the new, more clean montage implementation, which is now accepting `multichannel` argument, performs padding between images and on the all 4 borders, uses memory more efficiently. Also, there were some bugs in `montage2d` which are fixed in `montage`;
- Significantly improved the docstring;
- Refactored the tests for `montageXX` functions, and added __a lot__ of new tests for `montage`;
- Updated the gallery examples to use `montage` instead of `montage2d`.

- Fixed some imports (`color/colorlabel` and `exposure/_adapthist`) to avoid cyclic dependencies with the new availability of `montageXX` functions (i.e. as `skimage.util.montage2d`, `skimage.util.montage`).

_To summarize:_
This PR implements new `skimage.util.montage` function which operates in a similar way as previous `skimage.util.montage.montage2d`, but also provides `padding_width` and `multichannel` (now working or multichannel images) arguments.
I'd insist on breaking the API here: moving `skimage.util.montage.montage2d` to `skimage.util.montage2d`, and having a short deprecation cycle for `montage2d` function. There is absolutely no need to hide a single function under a separate module.

