@petri I don't think the two approaches are mutually exclusive.

The benefit of this approach is that it allows developers to define their interactions with pypiserver via the `entry_points` mechanism, which will allow pypiserver to automatically discover and load their patches/updates if they are installed. Otherwise, plugin authors would somehow have to make sure that users were loading their plugins at runtime, or running `pypiserver` via some kind of proxy offered by the installed plugin package. Please correct me if I'm wrong, obviously, but I think that's the primary advantage.

In the medium term, I also like the idea of adding plugin groups that function more directly in different interface areas.

