@ericwallen, you may have more luck making a post on https://community.letsencrypt.org where there is a more active community.

The technical details about what's going on is Certbot is trying to configure Apache to serve a different certificate for a randomly generated domain name in order to prove to Let's Encrypt that you control devfaction.com. Certbot is unable to do this though either do to a bug in our software or your server's configuration. In order to help you further, I need to see more details of your Apache configuration. For starters, I'd like to see the virtual hosts you have and more specifically the HTTP and HTTPS vhosts for devfaction.com.

Alternatively, you may want to consider switching to a shared hosting provider that has already integrated with Let's Encrypt rather than Go Daddy. This would make the process much easier for you. You can find a list of such hosting providers at https://www.godaddy.com/help/install-a-lets-encrypt-ssl-apache-20245. While Go Daddy is listed, they simply provide instructions to download and run Certbot which unfortunately hasn't been working for you so far. Many hosting providers on the other hand allow you to enable HTTPS for free with a certificate from Let's Encrypt with the click of a button.

